			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">*mumbles something really nasty about Doom III and modern game development*
<br />

<br />
The days of high graphics are reaching an end - maybe now we'll see somebody actually making CONTENTS *gasp* The storyline of Doom III or even the one of Far Cry for that matter won't be tolerated once the peak of graphics has been reached, since people have seen plenty of nice graphics for such a long time to not be stunned by it anymore. Whatever else they make in the graphics department, will make it look slightly more realistic and slightly more detailed over the next years, but large scale innovations on the area we won't see for a -very- long time. Not until a complete remake of how we deal with graphics in today's FPS is pulled through... Can anybody hear Santa's bells ringing in july? No? Because that'll happen before we see anything really breathtaking again with graphics in computer games.
<br />

<br />
As for AO, it's been due for a graphical overhaul for quite a while... It won't happen though. It'll still be slow, choppy, and based on an outdated engine, not utilizing the potential of the graphics cards. Hail to the texture people at FC who make the game seem prettier than it actually is!
<br />

<br />
Nice card though - fail to see the use admittingly, since the GPU's performance rates still are increasing and generally I think it'll be better possible to get better render speeds from one high tuned card (which is already cheaper than two medium-sized). That was the problem with the V2-V3 series - that it increased speed by approx 50-70% on GPU calculations at the time - and was still slower than the single cards with, for example, TNT2 chips that came out only short time after the release of SLI for V2. I doubt the picture will be any different for GF SLI, despite the awesome potential in the PCI Express standard combined with SLI.
<br />

<br />
Oh well, won't be the first time I'm wrong, and I hope I am. I doubt it though...
<br />

<br />
~Zionai</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
