			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">What is interesting is that Valve decided to not go for all out realism but toned it down and tried not to over do it. (as stated in one of the interviews with them) 
<br />

<br />
And I really understand it. Doom III will have more "awesome" details etc. etc.
<br />
than Half-Life 2 but will it have as good a feel as I suspect HL2 will? I don't think so. 
<br />

<br />
D3 and HL2 are perfect examples of current medium hitting a virtual limit. 
<br />
D3 squeezes the hardware pretty hard, yet I doubt the looks will be that much different from say HL2 that opted for a more toned down realism for practical reasons. 
<br />

<br />
Photorealism games will never really be a hit (yet). 
<br />
Did anyone see The Animatrix and the first chapter called Last Flight of the Osiris? that is pretty much close to the state of the art CG (and took a year to make? O.o) 
<br />
Scenes like that will take less and less time to make, details will get a tad higher but not much, and in a few years since like that is fully possible in real-time. D2 engine is getting damn close, HL2 engine right behind but opting for a slightly softer realism and more cinematic style scenes and scenery. 
<br />

<br />
So I def agree, graphics hardware will start to flatten it's curve and move towards optimization, speed improvements, memory etc. 
<br />
And now and again some new feature that tries to help offload the cpu. 
<br />
Most likely the more dramatic improvements in that area will be the moving of more cpu world geometry calculations into the GFX card, 
<br />
possible AI and collision detection will be even more moved over to the GFX card etc. 
<br />
Audio cards of the higher models already have very advanced sound dynamics (and audio occlusion and other advanced audio physics) 
<br />

<br />
What I estimate is the next step is VR and I'm not just talking stereoscopic/shutter glasses stuff. But actual VR headgear with no side view 
<br />
leakage (openings) that let you see your room. But fully enclosed headgear/visors. Using LCD or OLED technology, fully dual screen progressive, with the card link options appearing and also most cards having dual monitor connectors/support this is easier too) 
<br />
And with head tracking allowing your head movement to steer mouse look/view direction. 
<br />

<br />
Such VR gears exist, but resolution suck, most are shutter/stereoscopic based and not so good for the eyes. Some are huge and bulky, 
<br />
others have open sides allowing real world to disturb your field of view. 
<br />

<br />
I truly hope improvements in this area increases rapidly as that would not allow even great realism and immersion, 
<br />
but will allow game makers etc to use the same gear and actually "design" in real 3d rather than staring at monitors. 
<br />
That will cause a dramatic change in realism. Having actually 3D, vs. staring at a monitor is like comparing old black and white TV’s with state of the art digital HDTV's. 
<br />

<br />
Although I'm impressed by Doom-III abilities, I must say that Half-Life 2 creators did the better choice. They could have squeezed the tech further, 
<br />
but for what gain? Less content but more pixel detail? 
<br />

<br />
Oh That’s another thing. Someone mentioned AO's strong point was it's textures. Maybe that is right. 
<br />
Games like HL2 and Doom3 etc, rise ad fall on their textures. 
<br />
Nobody want to stand close to a wall and see blurry lines etc. 
<br />
But using bigger and bigger textures aren’t always the solution, somebody have to make them and that is a real time consumer and pain in the ass for a gfx artist. Not to mention the cost in work hrs. 
<br />

<br />
So usually in modern games you may see lots of awesome textures, 
<br />
but.. Have you ever looked at the ground/floors and other places like on tables and walls etc. Even tough they have lots of details, they still appear 
<br />
very "clean" there is no dust, smudges nor imperfections. 
<br />
Maybe it's a lack of bump mapping or dirt shaders etc? Who knows! 
<br />
Still I feel that walking down a street no matter how awesome and what tech the game runs on. It still is miles away from "real world" look. 
<br />

<br />
They use terms like photorealism, which make me laugh. 
<br />
Most photos we see have been enhanced or doctored in some way. 
<br />
Same with movies ad TV, use of unnatural lighting and light filters etc 
<br />
in both the studio and editing room changes it. 
<br />

<br />
Photorealism isn't realism, photorealism is photorealism. 
<br />
I think Valve noticed that and decided to tone it down and use those resources elsewhere to improve the gaming and story experience. 
<br />
Only way realism can be achieved is by going true 3D, a 2D based monitor 
<br />
whether you use shutter glasses (that just enhance depth of field) is far from true 3D no matter what the card makers and game makers tell you. 
<br />

<br />
You actually CAN get proper VR headgear with head tracking, unfortunately it costs damn much... at least for normal consumers. 
<br />

<br />
So cheers to the future, and here's hoping we'll have ATI Radeon VR cards with VR headgear w/head tracking, or a NVIDIA equivalent GF card with VR headgear w/head tracking etc.<br />_________________<br />Author of Gridbot, DJ-Bot, Callerbot - <a href="http://www.gridstream.com" target="_blank">http://www.gridstream.com</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
